<div class="header">
  <div class="header-content">
    <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</div>
    <h1>McKesson (MCK)<br/>Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A transparent discounted cash flow valuation of McKesson Corporation. Using the latest actuals, mathematically derived assumptions, and one final number.</p>
    <p class="date">Updated March 24, 2026</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice !== null ? currentPrice.toFixed(2) : 'N/A'} ({marginOfSafety}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. To eliminate bias, we strictly derived every input mathematically from current fundamental data rather than fabricating arbitrary constants.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>McKesson generated <strong>${fcf2025 !== null ? fcf2025.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'} million</strong> in free cash flow in the most recent fiscal year.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow FCF at <strong>{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(2)}% per year</strong> for 5 years. This is the exact 4-year historical CAGR derived from McKesson's FCF growth from FY21 to FY25.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(2)}% forever</strong>. This is capped mathematically at half of the current 10-Year Treasury yield, acknowledging that no company can outgrow the broader economy in perpetuity.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>Future cash flows are discounted at <strong>{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(2)}%</strong>. This required rate of return is the sum of the Risk-Free Rate (10Y Treasury at 4.18%) plus the company's current Free Cash Flow Yield.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (${netCash !== null ? netCash.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'}M) = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding ({sharesOutstanding !== null ? sharesOutstanding.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'}M) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>Mathematically Derived Assumptions</h2>
  <p>Unlike standard models that rely on fabricated "standard" equity risk premiums or guessed growth rates, all three core variables in this model are computationally derived from the market.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(2)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Derived by calculating the Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) of McKesson's Free Cash Flow from FY2021 (${fcfHistory[4]}M) to FY2025 (${fcfHistory[0]}M). This anchors near-term projections precisely to actual historical performance rather than analyst speculation.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(2)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Calculated as the 10-Year Treasury Yield (4.18%) plus McKesson's current Free Cash Flow Yield ({(fcfYield * 100).toFixed(2)}%). This dynamically adjusts the required return based on the actual cash yield the market is currently demanding for the stock.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(2)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Computed strictly as exactly half of the 10-Year Treasury yield. This serves as a mathematically grounded, conservative proxy for long-term GDP growth, ensuring the terminal value doesn't artificially inflate the valuation.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>FCF ($M)</th>
          <th>PV Factor</th>
          <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Base (FY2025)</td>
          <td>${fcf2025 !== null ? fcf2025.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'}</td>
          <td>—</td>
          <td>—</td>
        </tr>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td>Year {p.year}</td>
            <td>${p.fcf.toLocaleString()}</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(4)}</td>
            <td>${p.pvFCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td colspan="3">Sum of Phase 1 PV</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
  <h3>Terminal Value & Final Calculation</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>PV of Phase 1 Cash Flows</td>
          <td>${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
          <td>${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>= Enterprise Value</td>
          <td>${enterpriseValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>+ Net Cash (Cash − Debt)</td>
          <td>${netCash !== null ? netCash.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>= Equity Value</td>
          <td>${equityValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>÷ Shares Outstanding</td>
          <td>{sharesOutstanding !== null ? sharesOutstanding.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>Intrinsic Value Per Share</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>The matrix below shows how intrinsic value per share changes depending on shifts in the Discount Rate (rows) and the Phase 1 Growth Rate (columns). The base case is highlighted.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={Math.abs(g - growthRatePhase1) < 0.001 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(1)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={Math.abs(row.dr - discountRate) < 0.001 && Math.abs(sensitivityGrowth[i] - growthRatePhase1) < 0.001 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks & Limitations</h2>
  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Aggressive Buybacks:</strong> McKesson has a strong track record of repurchasing shares. If they continue shrinking the float faster than historical averages, the per-share value will increase beyond this static projection.</li>
    <li><strong>Margin Expansion:</strong> As a wholesale distributor, MCK operates on razor-thin margins. Even a tiny percentage point increase in operating margin due to efficiency gains or specialty pharmaceuticals can translate to massive FCF leaps.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Drug Pricing Legislation:</strong> Any federal mandates capping prescription drug prices or altering pharmacy benefit manager (PBM) structures could permanently impair revenue growth and compress margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Customer Consolidation:</strong> McKesson's customer base (large pharmacy chains) is heavily concentrated. Loss of a major contract or aggressive price negotiation from massive retail chains could threaten the projected cash flows.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use mathematical derivation instead of standard WACC?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Standard WACC often relies on arbitrary, fabricated estimates for Equity Risk Premium (ERP) and Beta. By deriving the discount rate from the actual 10Y Treasury yield plus the real-time Free Cash Flow Yield, the model self-corrects based on what the market is actually demanding for the asset today.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the terminal growth rate capped?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No individual corporation can outgrow the broader economy into infinity. Capping the terminal rate at half the 10Y Treasury yield enforces a mathematically rigorous ceiling on perpetuity value, preventing the DCF from generating dangerously optimistic "hockey stick" valuations.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Does this account for McKesson's debt load?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Yes. The model subtracts Total Debt and adds Cash & Equivalents to bridge Enterprise Value to Equity Value. If a company carries heavy debt, it directly penalizes the final intrinsic value per share.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

